Dehumanization/universal inclusion link.\par
\par
Extending humanity as a universal concept for inclusion fails to rupture exclusion because it ontologically requires the ability to render certain subjects inhuman to sustain itself. This inevitably makes the very objectification they indict inevitable.\par
\par
Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\par
\par
\pard\sb100\sa100\f1 As soon as savages began to call 'men' only those who were members of their tribe, \ul\b the definition of the 'Human' \ulnone\b0 was considerably enlarged: it\ul\b  became a universal concept\ulnone\b0 . This is precisely what we call culture. Today all men are men. \ul\b Universality is in fact based exclusively on \ulnone\b0 tautology and \ul\b doubling, and this is where the 'Human' takes on the force of a\ulnone\b0  moral law and a \ul\b principle of exclusion\ulnone\b0 . This is \ul\b because the 'Human' is from the outset the institution of its structural double, the 'Inhuman\ulnone '\b0 . This is all it is: \ul\b the progress of Humanity and Culture are simply the chain of discriminations with which to brand 'Others' with inhumanity, and therefore with nullity\ulnone\b0 . For the savages who call themselves 'men', the others are something else. For us, by contrast, under the sign of the Human as a universal concept, \ul\b others are nothing\ulnone\b0 . In other cases, to be 'man' is, like being a gentleman, a challenge, a distinction experienced as a great struggle, not merely giving rise to an exchange of \i\f2 quality\i0  or status amongst different beings (gods, ancestors, foreigners, animals, nature . . .), but \i imposing\i0  its stakes universally, being praised and prohibited. \ul\b We are happy to be promoted to the universal, to an abstract and generic value indexed on the equivalence of the species, to the exclusion of all the others\ulnone\b0 . In some sense, therefore, the definition of the Human inexorably contracts in accordance with cultural developments: \ul\b each 'objective' progressive step towards the universal corresponded to an ever stricter discrimination\ulnone\b0 , \ul\b until\ulnone\b0  eventually we can glimpse the time of man's \ul\b definitive universality \ulnone\b0 that\ul\b  will coincide with the excommunication of all men \emdash  the purity of the concept alone radiant in the void\ulnone\b0 .\par
\f1 Racism is modern. Previous races or cultures were ignored or eliminated, but never under the sign of a universal Reason. There is no criterion of man, no split from the Inhuman, there are only differences with which to oppose death. But \ul\b it is our undifferentiated concept of man that gives rise to discrimination. \ulnone\b0 We must read the following narrative by Jean de L\'e9ry, from the sixteenth century: \i Histoire d'un voyage en la terre de Br\'e9sil\i0  ('The History of a Journey to the Land of Brazil') to see that \ul\b racism did not exist in this period when the Idea of Man does not yet cast its shadow over all the metaphysical purity of Western culture\ulnone\b0 . This Reformation puritan from Geneva, landing amongst Brazilian cannibals, is not racist. It is due to the extent of our progress that we have since become racists, and not only towards Indians and cannibals: the increasing hold of rationality on our culture has meant \ul\b the successive extradition of inanimate nature, animals and inferior races {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_126_Popup_1.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\super 1}}}\cf0\nosupersub\f1\fs24  into the Inhuman, \ulnone\b0 while \ul\b the cancer of the Human has invested the very society it claimed to contain within its absolute superiority. \ulnone\b0 Michel Foucault has analysed the extradition of madmen at the dawn of Western modernity, but we also know of the extradition and progressive confinement of children, following the course of Reason itself, into the idealised state of infancy, the ghetto of the infantile universe and the abjection of innocence. But the old have also become inhuman, pushed to the fringes of normality. Like so many others, the mad, children \f2 and the old have only become 'categories' under the sign of the successive segregations that have marked the development of culture. The poor, the under-developed, those with subnormal IQs, perverts, transsexuals, intellectuals and women form a folklore of terror, a folklore of excommunication on the basis of an increasingly racist definition of the 'normal human'. \ul\b Quintessence of normality: ultimately all these 'categories' will be excluded, segregated, exiled in a finally universal society, where the normal and the universal will at last fuse under the sign of the Human.\par
\ulnone\b0\par
Death Link\par
Exclusion of death from our normal interaction with politics is the ultimate biopolitical determination - the destruction of its overt significance has resulted in its displacement into ever more insidious mechanisms of functioning. This sets the foundational model for every form of exclusion.\par
\pard\f0 Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\f2\par
\pard\sb100\sa100\f1 Foucault's analysis, amongst the masterpieces of this genuine cultural history, takes the form of a genealogy of discrimination in which, at the start of the nineteenth century, labour and production occupy a decisive place. \ul\b At the very core of \ulnone\b0 the 'rationality' of \ul\b our culture\ulnone\b0 , however, \ul\b is an exclusion that precedes every other\ulnone\b0 , more radical than the exclusion of madmen, children or inferior races, an exclusion preceding all these \ul\b and serving as their model: the exclusion of the dead and of death\ulnone\b0 .\f2  \f1 There is an irreversible evolution from savage societies to our own: little by little,\ul\b  \i the dead cease to exist\ulnone\b0\i0 . They are \ul\b thrown out of the group's symbolic circulation\ulnone\b0 . They are \ul\b no longer beings with a full role to play\ulnone\b0 , worthy partners in exchange, and we make this obvious \ul\b by exiling them further and further away from the group of the living\ulnone\b0 . In the domestic intimacy of the cemetery, the first grouping remains in the heart of the village or town, becoming the first ghetto, prefiguring every future ghetto, but are thrown further and further from the centre towards the periphery, finally having nowhere to go at all, as in the new town or the contemporary metropolis, where there are no longer any provisions for the dead, either in mental or in physical space. Even madmen, delinquents and misfits can find a welcome in the new towns, that is, in the rationality of a modern society. Only the death-function cannot be programmed and localised. Strictly speaking\f2 , \ul\b we no longer know what to do with them, since, today, \i it is not normal to be dead\i0 , and this is new\ulnone\b0 . \ul\b To be dead is an unthinkable anomaly\ulnone\b0 ; nothing else is as offensive as this. Death is \ul\b a delinquency, and an incurable deviancy\ulnone\b0 . The dead are no longer inflicted on any place or space-time, they can find no resting place; they are thrown into a radical utopia. \ul\b They are no longer even packed in and shut up, but obliterated\ulnone\b0 .\ul\b\f1 But we know what these hidden places signify: the factory no longer exists because labour is everywhere\ulnone\b0 ; the prison no longer exists because arrests and confinements pervade social space-time; the asylum no longer exists because psychological control and therapy have been generalised and become banal; the school no longer exists because every strand of social progress is shot through with discipline and pedagogical training; capital no longer exists (nor does its Marxist critique) because the law of value has collapsed into self-managed survival in all its forms, etc., etc. \ul\b The cemetery no longer exists because modern cities have entirely taken over their function: they are ghost towns, cities of death\ulnone\b0 . If the great operational metropolis is the final form of an entire culture, then, quite simply, \ul\b ours is a culture of death\ulnone\b0 . {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_127_Popup_1.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 3}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f3\fs20\par
\par
\f0\fs24 And their simulation of death only defines life antithetically in relation to such - as such living is only prolonged death destroying the value to life.\par
Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\par
\f1 It is correct to say that \ul\b the dead, hounded and separated from the living, condemn us to an \i equivalent death\i0 : \ulnone\b0 for the fundamental law of symbolic obligation is at play in any case, for better or worse. Madness, then, is only ever the \i dividing\i0  line between the mad and the normal, a line which normality \i shares\i0  with madness and which is even defined by it. Every society that internalises its mad is a society invested in its depths by madness, which alone and everywhere ends up being symbolically exchanged under the legal signs of normality. Madness has for several centuries worked hard on the society which confines it, and today the asylum walls have been removed, not because of some miraculous tolerance, but because madness has \i completed\i0  its normalising labour on society: madness has become pervasive\f2 , while at the same time it is forbidden a resting place. The asylum has been reabsorbed into the core of the social field, because normality has reached the point of perfection and assumed the characteristics of the asylum, because the virus of confinement has worked its way into every fibre of 'normal' existence. \f1 So it is with death. \ul\b Death is ultimately nothing more than the social line of demarcation separating the 'dead' from the 'living': therefore, it affects both equally.\ulnone\b0  \ul\b Against the \ulnone\b0 senseless \ul\b illusion of the living of willing the living to the exclusion of the dead, against the illusion that reduces life to \i an absolute surplus-value\i0  by subtracting death from it, the indestructible logic of symbolic exchange re-establishes the equivalence of life and death in the indifferent fatality of survival.\ulnone\b0  In survival, \ul\b death is repressed; life itself, in accordance with that well known ebbing away, would be nothing more than a survival determined by death.\ulnone\b0\f2\par
\par
Their cordoning off of death necessitates the biopolitical manipulation of life to sustain their distance.\par
\f0 Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\f2\par
\f1 The emergence of \ul\b survival can \ulnone\b0 therefore \ul\b be analysed as the fundamental operation in the birth of power. \ulnone\b0 Not only because this set-up will permit the necessity of the sacrifice of this life and the threat of recompense in the\f2  \f1 next (this is exactly the priest-caste's strategy), but more profoundly \ul\b by instituting the \i prohibition of death\i0  \ulnone\b0 and, at the same time, the agency that oversees this prohibition of death: power. \ul\b Shattering the union of the living and the dead, and slapping a prohibition on death and the dead: the primary source of social control\ulnone\b0 . Power is possible only if death is no longer free, only if \ul\b the dead are put under surveillance, in anticipation of the future confinement of life in its entirety\ulnone\b0 . This is the fundamental Law, and power is the guardian at the gates of this Law. It is not the repression of unconscious pulsions, libido, or whatever other energy that is fundamental, and it is not anthropological; it is the repression of death, \ul\b the social repression of death \ulnone\b0 in the sense that this is what \ul\b facilitates the shift towards the repressive socialisation of life. \ulnone\b0 Historically, we know that sacerdotal power is based on a monopoly over death and exclusive control over relations with the dead. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_130_Popup_1.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 4}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f1\fs24  The dead are the first restricted area, the exchange of whom is restored by an obligatory mediation by the priests. \ul\b Power \ulnone\b0 is established on death's borders. It \ul\b will subsequently be sustained by further separations \ulnone\b0 (the soul and the body, the male and the female, good and evil, etc.) that have infinite ramifications, but the principal separation is between life and death.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_130_Popup_2.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 5}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f1\fs24  When the French say that \ul\b power 'holds the bar'\ulnone\b0 ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_130_Popup_3.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 6}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f1\fs24  it is no metaphor: it is the bar\ul\b  between life and death, the decree that suspends exchange between life and death\ulnone\b0 , the tollgate and border control between the two banks.\f2\par
\par
Cartesian Dualism Link\par
The management of death necessitates the alienation of the subject from their life and body mediating an ethical relation to life, and forming the foundation for EVERY FORM of control.\par
\f0 Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\f2\par
\f1 This is precisely the way in which \ul\b power will \ulnone\b0 later be \ul\b instituted between the subject separated from its body, between the individual separated from its social body, between man separated from his labour: the agency of mediation\ulnone\b0  and representation \ul\b flourishes in this rupture\ulnone\b0 . We must take note, however, that \ul\b the archetype of this operation is the separation between a group and its dead, or between each of us today and our own deaths\ulnone\b0 .\ul\b  Every form of power will have something of this smell about it, because it is on the manipulation and administration of death that power, \ulnone\b0 in the final analysis, is based. \ul\b All \ulnone\b0 the \ul\b agencies of repression and control are installed in this divided space\ulnone\b0 , in the suspense between a life and its proper end, that is, in the production of a literally fantastic and artificial temporality (since at every instant every life has its proper death there already, that is to say, in this same instant lies the finality it attains). The first abstract social time is installed in this rupture of the indivisible unity of life and death (well before abstract social labour time!). \ul\b All \ulnone\b0 the future \ul\b forms of alienation\ulnone\b0  that Marx denounces, the separations and abstractions of political economy,\ul\b  take root in this separation of death\ulnone\b0 .\f2\par
The affirmative's seperation of life and death necessitates their mutual constitution - Life as concieved of by the 1ac is haunted by an ever present negativity of death nullifying its value. Death is only possible as a metaphysical event insofar as we concieve of ourselves as alive.\par
\f0 Jean \ul\b Baudrillard\ulnone\b0 , Professor of Sociology @ University of Nanterre Paris, \ul\b 93\ulnone\b0 , \ul The Symbolic Exchange and Death\ulnone  Pg.____ (Giglio)\f2\par
\f1 The initiatory act is the reverse of our reality principle. It shows that the \i reality\i0  of birth derives solely from the separation of life and death. Even\ul\b  the \i reality\i0  of life itself derives solely from the disjunction of life and death\ulnone\b0 . The \i effect of the real\i0  is only ever therefore the structural effect of the disjunction between two terms, and our famous reality principle, with its normative and repressive implications, is only a generalisation of this disjunctive code to all levels. The reality of nature, its 'objectivity' and its 'materiality', derives solely from the separation of man and nature, of a body and a non-body, as Octavio Paz put it. \ul\b Even the reality of the body, its material status, derives from the disjunction of a spiritual principle, from discriminating a soul from a body\ulnone\b0\f2 . \f1 The symbolic is what puts an end to this disjunctive code and to separated terms. \i It is the u-topia that puts an end to the topologies of the soul and the body, man and nature, the real and the non-real, birth and death\i0 . In the symbolic operation, the two terms lose their reality. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_133_Popup_1.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 8}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f2\fs24  \f1 The reality principle is never anything other than the \i imaginary\i0  of the other term. In the man/nature partition, nature (objective, material) is only the imaginary of man thus conceptualised. In the sexual bipartition masculine/feminine, an arbitrary and structural distinction on which the sexual reality (and repression) principle is based, 'woman' thus defined is only ever man's imaginary. Each term of the \ul\b disjunction excludes the other, which eventually becomes its imaginary\ulnone\b0 . \ul\b So it is with life and death \ulnone\b0 in our current system: \ul\b the price we pay for the 'reality' of this life, to live it as a positive value, is the ever-present phantasm of death\ulnone\b0 . For us, defined as living beings, \ul\b death is our imaginary\ulnone\b0 .{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "JavaScript:doPopup('EndNote','Page_133_Popup_2.html','width=480,height=384,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes')"}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul\super\b 9}}}\cf0\ulnone\nosupersub\b0\f1\fs24  So, all the disjunctions on which the different structures of the real are based (this is not in the least abstract: it is also what separates the teacher from the taught, and on which the reality principle of their relation is based; the same goes for all the social relations we know) have their archetype in the fundamental disjunction of life and death. This is why,\ul\b  in whatever field of 'reality', every separate term for which the other is its imaginary is haunted by the latter as \i its own death\ulnone\b0\i0 .\f2\par
\f3\fs20\par
