Catastrophe management Kritik:\par
\par
The affirmative's fixation on anticipating and controlling future scenarios for disaster is symptomatic of an implicit death drive - it renders us psychologically comfortable with our death and instills a perverse desire to bring it upon ourselves.\par
\par
\ul\b\i Fisher\ulnone\b0\i0 , Economist and Associate Policy Director @ FRB of Atlanta, \ul\b\i 2000\ulnone\b0\i0  (Mark, Flatline Constructs: Gothic Materialism and Cybernetic Theory-Fiction, http://www.cinestatic.com/trans-mat/Fisher/FC2s11.htm)giglio\par
\pard\sb100\sa100\f2 In both The Atrocity Exhibition and the subsequent Crash - in many ways an extrapolation of a particular obsession from the previous book (the fusion of erotics and carcrashes) - Ballard describes a generalized traumatics, in which power and catastrophe simulate each other, becoming indistinguishable. \ul\b Catastrophes and their re-enactment circulate endlessly \ulnone\b0 in Ballard's chaosmos, not necessarily only as mechanical repetition of what has already happened, but also \ul\b as cybernetically anticipative simulations\ulnone\b0 . The implication is that, \ul\b by being projected in advance, any future possibility\ulnone\b0 , no matter how horrific, \ul\b can, in some sense, be "managed" \ulnone\b0 . \par
Faced with the apparently senseless spectacle of the protracted conflict in Vietnam - "All political and military explanations fail to provide a rationale for the war's extended duration" - Ballard seeks out its sources in a mediatized unconscious \ldblquote fixated to trauma.\rdblquote  Like \ul\b Freud, impelled to postulate the death drive in part by his observation of the behaviour of First World War shellshock victims as they obsessively re-enacted their trauma\ulnone\b0 , Ballard discovers in mediatized culture an obsessive "compulsion to repeat." \ul\b Repetition both serves to alleviate trauma and to perpetuate it\ulnone\b0 , wrecking any simple teleology: in the paradoxical logic Freud delineates in Beyond the Pleasure Principle, \ul\b the organism preserves itself precisely by becoming-inorganic, and \ldblquote life\rdblquote  is only a detour on the way to death\ulnone\b0 . \ul\b This emerges for Ballard at the level of deleometric catastrophe management systems in the form of perverse explanations for the war, \ulnone\b0 irrationales: "'In terms of television and the news magazines the war in \ul\b Vietnam\ulnone\b0  has a latent significance very different from its manifest content. Far from repelling us, it\ul\b  appeals to us by virtue of its complex of polyperverse acts\ulnone\b0 ." (AE 87) Media - as the ambivalently functioning additions to the human perceptual system described by Freud and McLuhan - have a crucial role to play in this economy: (an)aestheticization,\ul\b  the translation of trauma into repeated images which, no matter how horrific they initially appear, soon become banal\ulnone\b0 , in part by dint of repetition itself. \par
\pard "Freud characterizes trauma as an 'invasion', a breach in an otherwise efficacious barrier against stimuli,' infiltrating alien desires - xenopulsions - into the organism."{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "\\\\l "_ftn1""}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul [195]}}}\cf0\ulnone\f2\fs24  But rather than damping down xenopulsive excitation, Ballard's cybernetic systems seem to hunt out and obsessively pore over trauma. Initially, according to Anti-Oedipus, \ul\b an "anus-vampire\ulnone\b0 " (AO 228), capitalism\ul\b  is\ulnone\b0 , by the time of The Atrocity Exhibition, also\ul\b  a ghoul: mediatizing the feedback process of its own reproduction in endlessly reiterating loops of mass production and consumption of death\ulnone\b0 . Deleometrics is the key science of Ballard's \ul\b catastrophe management \ulnone\b0 - \ul\b the urge not now to banish death\ulnone\b0 , nor to suicidally embrace it (as according to Deleuze-Guattari, fascism had{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "\\\\l "_ftn2""}}{\fldrslt{\cf1\ul [196]}}}\cf0\ulnone\f2\fs24 ) \ul\b but to quantify it, to "optimize" it\ulnone\b0 . What Baudrillard calls the generalization of the Accident leads to what he characterizes as a \ldblquote hyperfunctionalism\rdblquote  which moves beyond both teleology and transgression. If the accident has become the rule, then there is no law to transgress, just as there is no goal to head towards.\par
\par
\par
The inevitable outcome of this framing of death is the artificial production of disaster to feed our own sick addiction.\par
\f3\fs20\par
\pard\sb100\sa100\ul\b\i\f2\fs24 Vukovic\ulnone\b0\i0 , Curator for the Student cultural center @ School of missing studies, \ul\b\i 99\ulnone\b0\i0  (Stevan, \cf2\f0 The Libidinal Economy of a 'Non-Existent War' in a 'Non-Existent Country' - Nostalgia for the End, "Stirring Streaming Dreaming" symposium)giglio\cf0\f2\par
According to Baudrillard's theory on \ul\b "catastrophe \ulnone\b0 management," this impossibility for Eastern Europe to integrate into the symbolic structure of the West, due to the outburst of uncontrollable enjoyment,\ul\b  is actually produced by the West itself, in order to be the source of \ldblquote fuel essential to the moral and sentimental equilibrium of the West\ulnone\b0 .\rdblquote\super\fs18 20\nosupersub\fs24  In the contemporary stage of capitalism, not only books, sport shoes and clothes for the West are being produced by the Western companies somewhere in the Third World, or in Eastern Europe - catastrophes are produced there as well. \ul\b\ldblquote Just as the economic crisis of the West will not be complete as long as it can still exploit the resources of the rest of the world, so the symbolic crisis will be complete only when it is no longer able to feed on the other half's human and natural catastrophes (\ulnone\b0 Eastern Europe, \ul\b the Gulf, the Kurds\ulnone\b0 , Bangladesh, etc.),\rdblquote\super\fs18 21\nosupersub\fs24  writes Baudrillard, describing the way\ul\b  the New Sentimental Order, as merely the last form of the New World Order, introduces new forms of exploitation\ulnone\b0 . Material exploitation, as old-fashioned and already out-of-date type of exploitation, \ldblquote is only there to extract that spiritual raw material that is\ul\b  the misery of the peoples\ulnone\b0 , which \ul\b serves as psychological nourishment for the rich countries and media nourishment for our daily lives.\rdblquote\ulnone\super\b0\fs18 22\nosupersub\fs24  \par
\pard\ul\b Catastrophe management \ulnone\b0 is the management of the Real, the post-symbolical Real that can be encountered only in the form of a catastrophe. Psychotic foreclosure and sliding into the Real \ul\b brings the subject into proximity too high to leave space for the representation of the Real\ulnone\b0 , without distance from jouissance that would make desire possible, turning it from the desiring object into the object of desire. As Ellie Ragland writes, \ldblquote the ego collapses into its own metonymic shadow and becomes the real object, the object a cause-of-desire,\rdblquote\super\fs18 23\nosupersub\fs24  \ul\b which\ulnone\b0  \ul\b functions as a drug\ulnone\b0 , as an aphrodisiac \ul\b that puts desire into motion \ulnone\b0 and a hallucinogen that, by the addition of an object, provides a vision of a subject supplied with "something more in oneself than oneself." \par
\par
Instead of endlessly prolonging catastrophe, imagining the inevitability of catastrophe as a starting point for discourse is critical to escape the ever present shadow the threat of catastrophe casts over life.\par
