\pard\ri288\ul\b One should\ulnone  \b0 thus \ul\b invert the existentialist commonplace according to which, when we are engaged in a present historical process, we perceive it as full of possibilities, and ourselves as agents free to choose among them; while, to a retrospective view, the same pro\-cess appears as fully determined and necessary, with no room for alternatives\ulnone : \ul on the contrary, it is the engaged agents who perceive themselves as caught in a Destiny, merely reacting to it, while, retrospectively\ulnone\b0 , from the standpoint of later observation, \ul\b we can dis\-cern alternatives in the past\ulnone\b0 , possibilities of events taking a different path. (And is not the attitude of Predestination\emdash the fact that the theology of predestination legitimized the frantic activity of capital\-ism\emdash the ultimate confirmation of this paradox?) \ul\b This is how\ulnone  \b0 Dupuy suggests that \ul\b we should confront the catastrophe\ulnone\b0 : we should \ul\b first perceive it as our fate\ulnone\b0 , as unavoidable, \ul\b and then, projecting our\-selves into it, adopting its standpoint, we should retroactively insert into its past (the past of the future) counterfactual possibilities (\ldblquote If we had done such and such a thing\b0 ,\ulnone  the catastrophe we are in now would not have happened!\rdblquote )\b  \ul upon which we then act today\b0 .\ulnone  And is not a supreme case of the reversal of positive into negative destiny the shift from classical historical materialism into the attitude of Adorno\rquote s and Horkheimer\rquote s \ldblquote dialectic of Enlightenment\rdblquote ? While traditional Marxism enjoined us to engage ourselves and act in order to bring about the necessity (of Communism), Adorno and Horkheimer projected themselves into the final catastrophic out\-come perceived as fixed (the advent of the \ldblquote administered society\rdblquote  of total manipulation and the end of subjectivity) in order to urge us 